   Myeongchan and Kim, Hyo Jung},
Title = {Enhancing COVID-19 Screening Models With Epidemiological and Mobility
   Features: Machine-Learning Model Study},
Journal = {JMIR AI},
Year = {2026},
Volume = {5},
Abstract = {Background: Despite the significant post-COVID-19 pandemic surge in
   research using symptom data and machine learning (ML) for patient
   screening, data on patient trajectories and epidemiological conditions,
   although crucial, have remained underused. Objective: This study aimed
   to enhance the performance of ML models for COVID-19 screening by
   incorporating mobility Methods: Data, including daily self-reported
   symptoms, location information, and test results, were collected from
   48,798 individuals using a smartphone app. These data were then combined
   with Our World in Data and national government epidemic information to
   train 5 ML-based screening models to classify patient infection status.
   The models were logistic regression, extreme gradient boosting, light
   gradient boosting machine, tabular data network, and Google AutoML.
   Results: The addition of mobility and epidemic data significantly
   improved the performance of all 5 models. The highest area under the
   receiver operating characteristic curve score increased from 0.8712
   without mobility and epidemic data to 0.9104 with mobility and epidemic
   data. This highlights the considerable impact of external information on
   enhancing the Conclusions: This study demonstrated the potential of
   using mobility and epidemic data, such as location information and
   epidemic data, in combination with patient symptom data to improve the
   accuracy of ML models for diagnosing COVID-19. Considering additional
   contextual information can enhance the ability to screen for COVID-19.},
Type = {Article},
Affiliation = {Kim, HJ (Corresponding Author), Catholic Univ Korea, Dept Biomed Software Engn, 43 Jibong Ro, Bucheon Si 14662, Gyeonggi Do, South Korea.
